04511nam a22006855i 9780801470615DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014706157 a10.7591/97808014706152doi  a(DE-B1597)496564  a(OCoLC)880451206  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0100002bisacsh1 aHelleiner, Eric, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForgotten Foundations of Bretton Woods :bInternational Development and the Making of the Postwar Order /cEric Helleiner. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2014] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Abbreviations -- tInternational Development and the North-South Dialogue of Bretton Woods -- t1. Good Neighbors Prepare the Ground -- t2. The First Draft: The Inter-American Bank -- t3. A New Approach to Money Doctoring: Cuba -- t4. Building Foundations: US Postwar Planning -- t5. Strengthening the Foundations: Paraguay -- t6. Latin American Backing for Bretton Woods -- t7. Development Aspirations in East Asia -- t8. Lukewarm and Inconsistent Britain -- t9. Enthusiasm from Eastern Europe and India -- tThe Aftermath and the Forgetting -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEric Helleiner's new book provides a powerful corrective to conventional accounts of the negotiations at Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, in 1944. These negotiations resulted in the creation of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank—the key international financial institutions of the postwar global economic order. Critics of Bretton Woods have argued that its architects devoted little attention to international development issues or the concerns of poorer countries. On the basis of extensive historical research and access to new archival sources, Helleiner challenges these assumptions, providing a major reinterpretation that will interest all those concerned with the politics and history of the global economy, North-South relations, and international development.The Bretton Woods architects—who included many officials and analysts from poorer regions of the world—discussed innovative proposals that anticipated more contemporary debates about how to reconcile the existing liberal global economic order with the development aspirations of emerging powers such as India, China, and Brazil. Alongside the much-studied Anglo-American relationship was an overlooked but pioneering North-South dialogue. Helleiner's unconventional history brings to light not only these forgotten foundations of the Bretton Woods system but also their subsequent neglect after World War II.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEconomic developmentxHistoryy20th century. 0aInternational financexHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147061540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801470615.jpg  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK